    "html": "<section class=\"catalog-card-content\"><div class=\"problem-body\">\n<p><strong>GETTING THERE</strong></p>\n<p>Elliott has been watching Dr. Frog take practice jumps all day. The frog keeps landing $15$ feet from the starting pad after making three hops. Answer the questions below to consider ways that Dr. Frog can travel $15$ feet in three hops.</p>\n<ol type=\"a\">\n<li>How many combinations of hops can you find to move Dr. Frog $15$ feet from where he started? Show your work with pictures, words, numbers, or symbols.</li>\n<li>Can the frog move $15$ feet in three equal hops?</li>\n<li>If two of the frog's hops are each $10$ feet long, how could you describe the third hop so that he still lands $15$ feet away from the starting pad? Is there more than one possibility?</li>\n</ol>\n<div class=\"figures\"><img alt=\"Frog making three hops for problem 3-89\" src=\"assets/lesson_3_2_1/3-89-frog-three-hops.png\"/></div>\n</div></section>",
